<HEADLINE>
<P>
JACQUES DEMY; DIRECTED 'UMBRELLAS OF CHERBOURG' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jacques Demy, 59, the French film director best known internationally for "The 
Umbrellas of Cherbourg," a revolutionary concept in motion pictures in which 
every word of dialogue was sung to a score by Michel Legrand. Trained as an 
animator and documentarian, Demy specialized in romantic, eloquent films rich 
in color. 
</P>
<P>
"The Umbrellas of Cherbourg" won the Golden Palm award at the 1964 Cannes film 
festival, but Demy never repeated its success despite the ambitious "Les 
Demoiselles de Rochefort" (The Young Girls of Rochefort), a similar picture 
that he directed two years later. Other films Demy directed and/or wrote in 
characteristic poetic style included "La Baie des Anges," "Peau d'Ane" and "The 
Pied Piper," filmed in Britain in 1972. He also made a film in the United 
States, "The Model Shop," which met with limited success. On Saturday in Paris 
of leukemia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
