<HEADLINE>
<P>
PLATFORM; 
</P>
<P>
DARING TO DREAM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TOM FLORES, TOM FLORES, general manager of the Seattle Seahawks, commented 
about the comparatively low numbers of American-born Latino athletes who move 
on to colleges and universities. He told The Times: 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
If these students were encouraged in some way to go on to college, then they 
would eventually excel in everything, including sports. But right now the 
problem is trying to get them to that point where they at least have the option 
of going to college after graduating from high school. 
</P>
<P>
A bigger question is, why aren't they graduating from high school? How to 
encourage them? I think it's a combination of everything. I didn't have that 
problem because I wanted to go on. But for a lot of my classmates, it was just 
a way of life -- not going on. We have to change that attitude. Attitude is 
very important, and until we change that, we're not going to have the rate of 
matriculation that we want in any ethnic group. 
</P>
<P>
Attitude goes into the family and the culture, everywhere. And you don't change 
attitude in a short period of time, especially when it has become a way of 
life. Right now, I think the way of life for a lot of these kids is the gangs, 
and that's scary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
