<HEADLINE>
<P>
FIRM HOPES CLEAN-AIR LAWS WILL BOOST SALES; 
</P>
<P>
GLENDALE: STRUGGLING POLLUTION RESEARCH AND CONTROL CORP. EXPECTS LEGISLATION 
TO INCREASE DEMAND FOR ITS EMISSIONS MONITORING DEVICES. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PATRICE APODACA, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Pollution Research and Control Corp. is a tiny Glendale company that makes 
devices for monitoring air pollution. Since it was founded in 1971, its success 
in the U.S. market had been limited, so in 1988 Pollution Research turned to 
overseas markets -- particularly South Korea -- which recently have accounted 
for more than half of its sales. 
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, the Korean market has proved an unsteady one for Pollution 
Research, and in the year that ended June 30, the company lost $1.45 million on 
$5.4 million in revenues. Not only were South Korean sales slipping, the same 
was true for domestic sales. 
</P>
<P>
But with President Bush expected to sign the new federal clean-air legislation, 
which aims to free the nation's skies of smog and other harmful forms of 
pollution by early in the next century, Pollution Research stands to 
participate in what could be a bonanza for companies that make pollution 
control and measurement products. These products will be needed by government 
agencies and factories to measure emissions of sulfur dioxide and other 
pollutants from smokestacks and in the surrounding air. 
</P>
<P>
"We see a very positive impact," said Albert E. Gosselin Jr., Pollution 
Research's president and chief executive. Gosselin estimated that the 
legislation could result over the next year in a more than $2-million jump in 
the company's sales. 
</P>
<P>
Gosselin said specific provisions in the legislation that will most directly 
help his company are those concerning acid rain. Pollution Research's monitors 
measure sulfur dioxide and oxides of nitrogen -- two of the key components of 
acid rain. Most of the electronic devices are about the size and shape of 
stereo receivers, cost $4,000 to $18,000, and analyze gases using ultraviolet 
light. 
</P>
<P>
Pollution Research hopes to sell more products to its traditional customers -- 
mostly utilities and government agencies such as the California Air Resources 
Board -- which will need the devices to monitor compliance with the new 
emissions standards. Orders may also come from consulting companies that buy 
the equipment on behalf of manufacturers, Gosselin said. 
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts agree that the clean-air legislation could be a boon for 
companies in the $50 million-a-year domestic air pollution monitoring business. 
"We're not just talking 20% or 30% growth here," said Stephen Schweich of Alex 
Brown &amp; Sons in Baltimore. "The market for emissions monitoring systems is 
going to expand geometrically," Schweich said. 
</P>
<P>
Analysts say Pollution Research also stands to benefit if Proposition 128 -- 
the "Big Green" initiative -- is passed by California voters next month. Big 
Green's clean-air provisions are even more stringent than those contained in 
the federal legislation. 
</P>
<P>
But John G. Taylor, an analyst at L.H. Alton &amp; Co. in San Francisco, 
cautioned that the clean-air legislation is still no guarantee that Pollution 
Research will manage a turnaround. 
</P>
<P>
"Just because the stage is set doesn't mean business is going to start walking 
in the door," Taylor said. "It's a question of executing a marketing plan and 
getting in front of enough people. I think the jury is still out as to whether 
they can do that." 
</P>
<P>
Pollution Research's track record has been spotty. Founded in 1971 by Gosselin, 
a mechanical engineer, Pollution Research (formerly named Dasibi Environmental 
Corp.) made a disastrous 1973 investment in a Colorado cattle ranch, from which 
it took the company several years to recover. The company has also fought an 
uphill, mostly losing, battle against its two biggest competitors. 
</P>
<P>
That's partly because the two competitors have the resources of large 
corporations to draw from. Massachusetts-based Thermo Instrument Systems is a 
division of Thermo Electron, which has annual sales of $400 million. Lear 
Siegler, a $2.5-billion concern, has a Colorado division that makes pollution 
monitoring equipment. 
</P>
<P>
To compete for contracts against its big rivals, Pollution Research more than 
doubled its staff to 86 workers from June to December of last year. But 
Gosselin said the increased overhead came at a time when domestic orders for 
pollution monitoring equipment started to slow as companies waited to see what 
the final clean-air legislation would contain. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, orders from South Korea's equivalent of the Environmental Protection 
Agency, a big Pollution Research customer, also started to dry up. 
</P>
<P>
Pollution Research entered the Korean market when it won a contract to monitor 
pollution at the 1988 Olympic Games in Seoul. Several orders worth about 
$400,000 apiece followed. 
</P>
<P>
But during the past year, Gosselin said, Korea stopped ordering pollution 
monitoring equipment, a result of various political changes. Gosselin said the 
Korean market is now opening up again, and he expects to land a contract soon 
that's worth more than $500,000. 
</P>
<P>
Gosselin also blamed Pollution Research's losses on "unethical" practices by 
Thermo Electron and Lear Siegler, including predatory pricing tactics. 
</P>
<P>
Arvin Smith, president of Thermo Instrument Systems, denied that his company 
had undercut Pollution Research's prices in hopes of driving it out of 
business. "We have the highest prices in the business," Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Pollution Research's troubles have been reflected in its stock, 
which traded as high as $2.375 a share in June, 1989, but closed Monday at 
18.75 cents a share. Gosselin said he has considered buyout offers from parties 
he declined to identify. But those talks have since broken off, and Gosselin 
said no other discussions are under way to sell the company. 
</P>
<P>
Gosselin said he has taken steps to try to turn the company around, including 
cutting the staff by more than half to 33 workers. He is also hoping to team up 
with larger partners, such as Brown Boveri, a big Swiss-Swedish concern with 
whom Pollution Research recently bid for a contract in Taiwan. Gosselin said he 
is also increasing marketing efforts in Europe, where he believes demand for 
pollution control products will soon take off. 
</P>
<P>
But Pollution Research's biggest hope is for the domestic market. By early next 
year, Gosselin said, government agencies and companies will start having plans 
and funding in place to comply with the new law, and "they're going to need our 
instruments." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Pollution Research and Control At A Glance 
</P>
<P>
Pollution Research and Control is a Glendale company that makes equipment for 
monitoring air pollution from smokestacks and in the surrounding air. Founded 
in 1971 by Albert E. Gosselin Jr., a mechanical engineer, the company has 33 
employees. 
</P>
<P>
For Fiscal years ended June 30; in millions 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Chart, Pollution Research and Control At A Glance, Los Angeles Times; Photo, 
Central processor unit, top, is "the brain of the instruments" made to monitor 
air quality, says Pollution Research President Albert E. Gosselin Jr., above. 
RICARDO DeARATANHA / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
</DOC>
