<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIZ SMITH: DEATH OF HER FATHER ADDS TO TROUBLES OF IVANA TRUMP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LIZ SMITH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAST WEEK, Ivana Trump struck me as lonely and upset, sitting in the baroque 
gilt splendor of the Trump Tower penthouse. Now we add the loss of her father 
to these feelings. Milos Zelnicek, 63, died of a heart attack Saturday and 
Ivana, her aide Lisa, and the three children are all in Czechoslovakia. 
</P>
<P>
It's no small thing for Ivana to lose her tall, handsome, supportive father. He 
has been her strong right arm all her life and a devoted and helpful 
grandfather to the little Trumps. Now he is gone. 
</P>
<P>
Ivana has to be very strong herself to go on without her wonderful dad. 
</P>
<P>
IT'S NO secret anymore that French actor Yves Montand entered into an affair 
with Marilyn Monroe during the making of their aptly titled 1960 movie "Let's 
Make Love." But just how serious was this dangerous liaison? Montand was 
married to Simone Signoret, MM to Arthur Miller. 
</P>
<P>
Well, according to a new biography, just published in Europe, it was very 
serious indeed. Montand is quoted in "You See, I Have Not Forgotten" by Herve 
Harmon and Patrick Rothman: "Not for a second did I envisage breaking with my 
wife, but if she had slammed the door, I probably would have made my life with 
Marilyn. Or tried to. Perhaps it would have lasted only two or three years. But 
what years!" 
</P>
<P>
And despite the fact that their romance came during what is considered to be 
the beginning of the end for Marilyn, Montand says: "I knew Marilyn for six 
months, and not once did she behave like the unbalanced person people have made 
her out to be. . . . Marilyn was an exceptional woman." 
</P>
<P>
This book also traces Simone Signoret's terrible physical decline (she went 
somewhat beyond the natural aging process). And the authors opine that Yves' 
affair with Marilyn exacerbated her eating, drinking and smoking. Montand 
recalls: "What I found hardest to accept was this form of self-destruction. The 
more she demolished herself the more I loved her." 
</P>
<P>
Signoret was characteristically Gallic. She was sanguine and sympathetic about 
Marilyn and Yves in all her public pronouncements at the time. Years later in 
her wonderful autobiography, she maintained this dispassionate distance. But, 
according to her friend Catherine Deneuve, "Marilyn remained carved on her face 
like an unhealed wound." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
